<p><a name="Tips" id="Tips"></a></p>
</div>
<h2><a href="/index.php?title=Safely-Use-a-Public-Bathroom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Tips" id="gatEditSection" class="button button52 editsection" onmouseover="button_swap(this);" onmouseout="button_unswap(this);" onclick="gatTrack(gatUser,'Edit','Edit_section');" name="gatEditSection">Edit</a> <span>Tips</span></h2>
<div id="tips" class='article_inner editable'>
<ul>
<li>If possible, avoid touching the door handles or doors to the restroom after you have washed your hands. Studies have found higher concentrations of bacteria on public restroom door handles than anywhere else in the restroom. Not everybody washes their hands on the way out. If you must open a door to exit, use a paper towel.</li>
<li>Flush before using the toilet if anything but water is visible in it.</li>
<li>When wiping, layer your toilet paper more than you normally would. The toilet paper in public bathrooms is cheap and thin. You don't want anything on your hands after a wipe.</li>
<li>Hovering is a quick, clean and safe method to go and especially preferable if the restroom is dirty, there is no toilet paper, you don't want spent time on lining or if you generally feel uncomfortable with sitting on a public toilet.</li>
<li>If you can't find a stall with toilet paper, hover and drip-dry after your business. But note: hovering and drip-drying are risky for leaving pee-dribbles on the seat.</li>
<li>Choose the urinal furthest from the door i.e a corner or next to a wall.</li>
<li>If you have to go really bad, don't invest time in preparing the toilet seat while wetting your pants -and don't sit on a unprepared seat. Hover, but with regard to your thigh-muscles and expecting a long pee-session, don't hover too low.</li>
<li>Some people forget to flush the toilet, making their waste visible to the next user of that stall. Don't do that yourself, or you will gross out the next stall user.</li>
<li>When using a Port-a-Potty use the urinal (men) or hover (women). Never sit, also if the toilet seat looks clean and dry. Note: the latrine-hole in a Port-a-Potty is a lot smaller, than in a normal toilet. This fact makes hovering and aiming more difficult and not peeing on the seat nearly impossible. (But don't mind, no one will blame you for leaving a peed seat in a Port a Potty). Use your own toilet paper or tissues.</li>
<li>Paper toilet seat covers are NOT going to protect you. If the seat is clean and dry, it's as clean as it gets. There are no infectious diseases carried by somebody's buttocks or thighs. If there are, the covers made from thin papers will not help. If you're serious about hygiene, don't sit on the seat but hover.</li>
<li>Hold children (girls) above the toilet or use or make a liner for them.</li>
<li>If the restroom in a business needs attention, notify the staff. They may not even know that there's a problem.</li>
<li>If you are to short to hover (especially young girls) or if you can't, due to other reasons, wipe the seat and sit on your hands while lifting your butt.</li>
<li>If going to use a toilet on a train or a plane, lift the seat first when peeing standing up (men) to avoid sprinkling the seat. Females should hover over the toilet: Replace the seat (if necessary)and wipe off any sprinkles before starting to hover-pee, only in case you fail to hold balance. Hovering in a higher position will give you better control in holding balance. Note: Because of the swaying transport, the smaller latrine-hole in trains and planes and hovering in a higher position this makes aiming a lot more difficult and may result in spraying pee on the seat (don't feel ashamed if you just leave without wiping off the mess you made).</li>
</ul>
<p><a name="Related_wikiHows" id="Related_wikiHows"></a></p>
</div>
